TY  - JOUR
AU  - Müller-Dethard, Jan
AU  - Reinhardt, Niklas
AU  - Weber, Martin
T1  - Reinvesting or Consuming Dividends: Account Structure Matters
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfaf031
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 29
IS  - 5
SP  - 1467
EP  - 1495
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - It is a long-standing fact that households mostly consume and rarely reinvest dividends. Among representative brokerage clients of one of Germany’s largest banks, we find the opposite: 80 percent reinvestments and 12 percent consumption. Of these reinvestments, the majority occurs with a delay after dividends are initially parked as brokerage cash. Motivated by this finding, we study payout modalities (deposits into brokerage accounts, checking accounts, or checks) as a novel mechanism that nudges investors toward reinvesting or consuming dividends. Consistent with a transition from checks to brokerage deposits, we find that the dividend consumption rate in the Consumer Expenditure Survey has decreased substantially over time.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfaf031
ER  - 




